<section xml:id="sec_row_ech_exer">
  <title>Exercises</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Represent the following linear system in variables
        <m>x_1, x_2, x_3</m> in augmented matrix form and use row reduction to find the general solution of the system.
        <md>
          <mrow> {}x_1   \amp {}+{}  \amp {}x_2  \amp {}-{}  \amp {}x_3   \amp = \amp {}4\amp {}</mrow>
          <mrow>{}x_1  \amp {}+{}  \amp {2}x_2 \amp {}+{}  \amp {2}x_3 \amp = \amp {}3\amp {}</mrow>
          <mrow>{2}x_1  \amp {}+{}  \amp {3}x_2 \amp {}-{}  \amp {3}x_3 \amp = \amp {}11\amp {.}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Represent the following linear system in variables
        <m>x_1, x_2, x_3</m> in augmented matrix form after rearranging the terms and use row reduction to find all solutions to the system.
        <md>
          <mrow>x_1 - x_3 - 2x_2 \amp = 3</mrow>
          <mrow>2x_3 + 2 \amp = x_1 +x_2</mrow>
          <mrow>4x_2 + 2x_1 - 2 \amp = 5x_3</mrow>
        </md>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Check that the reduced row echelon form of the matrix
        <me>
          \left[ \begin{array}{rrrr} 1 \amp -1\amp  3\amp  2 \\ -1\amp  2\amp -4\amp -1 \\ 2\amp 0\amp 6\amp 8 \end{array}  \right]
        </me>
        is
        <me>
          \left[ \begin{array}{cccc} 1 \amp 0\amp 0\amp 1 \\ 0\amp 1\amp 0\amp 2 \\ 0\amp 0\amp 1\amp 1 \end{array}  \right] \,
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider the following system:
        <md>
          <mrow> {}x   \amp {}-{}   \amp {2}y   \amp {}+{}   \amp {}z     \amp {}={}  \amp \ {-}\amp 1\amp {}</mrow>
          <mrow>{}    \amp {}    \amp {2}y  \amp {}-{}   \amp {4}z  \amp {}={}   \amp  \ {}\amp 6\amp {}</mrow>
          <mrow>{}    \amp {}    \amp {h}y  \amp {}-{}   \amp {2}z  \amp {}={}   \amp  \ {}\amp 1\amp {.}</mrow>
        </md>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a row echelon form of the augmented matrix for this system.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For which values of <m>h</m>, if any,
              does the system have (i.) no solutions, (ii.) exactly one solution, (iii.) infinitely many solutions?
              Find the solutions in each case.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the general solution of the linear system corresponding to the following augmented matrix:
        <me>
          \left[ \begin{array}{rrcr|r} 1\amp -1\amp 2\amp 1\amp 2 \\ -1\amp 2\amp 2\amp -1\amp -5\\ 1\amp 1\amp 10\amp 2\amp -1 \end{array}   \right]
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        What are the conditions, if any, on the
        <m>a,
        b, c</m> values so that the following augmented matrix corresponds to a consistent linear system?
        How many solutions will the consistent system have?
        Explain.
        <me>
          \left[ \begin{array}{rrr|c} 1 \amp  2 \amp  3 \amp a \\ 2\amp 3\amp 7\amp b \\ -1\amp -4\amp -1\amp c \end{array}   \right]
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        In this exercise the symbol
        <m>\blacksquare</m> denotes a non-zero number and the symbol * denotes any real number
        (including <m>0</m>).
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Is the augmented matrix
              <me>
                \left[ \begin{array}{cc|c} \blacksquare\amp *\amp * \\ 0\amp \blacksquare\amp * \end{array}  \right]
              </me>
              in a form to which back substitution will easily give the solutions to the system?
              Explain your reasoning.
              <hint>
                <p>
                  In order to help see what happens in the general case,
                  substitute some numbers in place of the
                  <m>\blacksquare</m>'s and *'s and answer the question for that specific system first.
                  Then determine if your answer generalizes.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The above matrix is a possible form of an augmented matrix with 2 rows and 3 columns corresponding to a linear system after forward elimination,
              i.e., a linear system for which back substitution will easily give the solutions.
              Determine the other possible such forms of the nonzero augmented matrices with 2 rows and 3 columns.
              As in part (a), use the symbol
              <m>\blacksquare</m> to denote a non-zero number and * to denote any real number.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Give an example of a linear system with a unique solution for which a row echelon form of the augmented matrix of the system has a row of 0's.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Come up with an example of an augmented matrix with 0's in the rightmost column corresponding to an inconsistent system,
        if possible.
        If not, explain why not.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find two different row echelon forms which are equivalent to the same matrix not given in row echelon form.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Determine all possible row echelon forms of a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix.
        Use the symbol <m>\blacksquare</m> to denote a non-zero number and * to denote a real number with no condition on being 0 or not to represent entries.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Label each of the following statements as True or False.
        Provide justification for your response.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> The number of pivots of an
              <m>m \times n</m> matrix cannot exceed <m>m</m>.
              (Note: Here <m>m</m>, <m>n</m> are some unknown numbers.)
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> The row echelon form of a matrix is unique.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> The reduced row echelon form of a matrix is unique.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> A system of equations where there are fewer equations than the number of unknowns
              (known as an underdetermined system)
              cannot have a unique solution.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> A system of equations where there are more equations than the number of unknowns
              (known as an overdetermined system)
              cannot have a unique solution.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If a row echelon form of the
              <em>augmented matrix</em>
              of a system of three equations in two unknowns has three pivots,
              then the system is inconsistent.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If the coefficient matrix of a system has pivots in every row,
              then the system is consistent.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If there is a row of zeros in a row echelon form of the augmented matrix of a system of equations,
              the system has infinitely many solutions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If there is a row of zeros in a row echelon form of the augmented matrix of a system of <m>n</m> equations in <m>n</m> variables,
              the system has infinitely many solutions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If a linear system has no free variables,
              then the system has a unique solution.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If a linear system has a free variable,
              then the system has infinitely many solutions.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</section>